ce:section.ce:para:
The PGM provided reasonable results for sodium and potassium nitrate, water, and argon [37], but underpredicts most alkali halides. Predictions for both actinide and non-actinide-bearing salts display similar levels of deviation from experimental results. Accuracy generally improves where ions are large and complex (such as in nitrates) or significant ionic charge-to-radii ratios exist (such as with high-concentration actinide mixtures or small, strongly bonding ions like Be
2 +
). This indicates a potential underestimation of the mean free path term, where the minimum interaction distance does not capture the actual propagation distance of energy carriers for all structure types.

The principal difference between the KTM and PGM lies in the assumptions regarding the adaptation of Eq. (1) to liquid thermal conductivity. Kinetic theory analogies such as the KTM and PGM are fundamentally composed of three parameters that govern heat transfer by energy carriers: the transferable energy carried in the direction of heat transfer (

                                 c
                                 3

                           ), the velocity of these carriers (
                              v
                           ), and their mean free path (
                              ℓ
                           ).

According to this relationship, weaker bonds would feature a smaller ratio between the first peak height g (
r
p e a k
) and following minimum g (
r min
) . This reflects a comparable treatment by Hines and Walls to quantify self-diffusion using the PDF [85]. The factor is calculated only for these positions and is thus not radially dependent, though it is applied at each integer multiple of Δ r . It provides a maximum relative bond strength given an ideal recipient ion, and therefore also serves to provide an estimated upper limit to the contribution of bond strength.

Yang et al. also questioned the temperature dependence of experimental data when it yielded a positive relation, given the theoretical reasons for a decreasing thermal conductivity with temperature and the increasing radiative or convective contributions with temperature that may conflate the measured conductivity. Comparisons to experimental data between varied compositions will thus be evaluated at the melting temperature or minimum experimentally measured temperature (above
T 0
). Case studies of a few salts will focus on the temperature dependence of the predicted versus measured thermal conductivity, yielding insights that may support the yet-inconclusive dependency on temperature.

Rather than suggesting a parameter-complete model, this work elucidates the essential properties involved in k for molten salts, while demonstrating a phenomenological relationship between the mean free path and the molten salt PDF. Depending on the reliability of specific heat and sound velocity, this reduces the problem of building empirical thermal conductivity correlations (based on highly variable data sources for
k exp
) to correlating composition-dependent PDF attributes. This opens the door to extrapolation of the PDF parameters themselves through empirical potential refinement techniques and machine learning when data is limited [158–160]. Obtaining the PDF for the limitless possible molten salt compositions is clearly prohibitive, but only a few essential parameters are needed to predict the structural coherence length. Rather than needing simulations to obtain the entire PDF, a predictive model may leverage relationships between unary PDFs and ML models of their mixture behavior. A structure-informed PDF model may also rely on machine-learning based models that build compositionally dependent, discretized PDFs [161]. Implementing these approaches to more fully parametrize the SCM is an objective of future work.
